{"title_page": "Munawar Hasan", "text_new": "{{Use Pakistani English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   =\n|name               = Syed Munawwar Hasan\n|native_name        = \u0633\u06cc\u062f \u0645\u0646\u0648\u0631 \u062d\u0633\u0646\n|native_name_lang   = ur\n|honorific-suffix   = \n|image              =\n|imagesize          = \n|smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n|alt                = \n|caption            = \n|order              = [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan|Emir of Jamaat-e-Islami]]\n|office             = \n|term_start         = 29 March 2009\n|term_end           = 29 March 2014\n|succeeding         = \n|predecessor        = [[Qazi Hussain Ahmad]]\n|successor          = [[Siraj-ul-Haq]]\n|birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1941|08|05}}\n|birth_place        = [[Dehli]], [[British India]]\n|nationality        = [[British Subject]] (1944\u20131947)<br/>{{PAK}} (1947\u2013present)\n|party              = [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan|Jamaat-e-Islami]]\n|occupation         = Religious Leader,<br/>Politician,<br/>Foreign policy commentator\n|alma_mater         = [[University of Peshawar]]<br/>(<small>BSc, MSc</small>)\n|profession         = Professor, religious leader\n}}\n\n'''Syed Munawar Hasan''' ({{lang-ur| \u0633\u06cc\u062f \u0645\u0646\u0648\u0631 \u062d\u0633\u0646}}; (born 5 August 1941) in [[Dehli]]) is a politician and the former [[Emir|Ameer]] (President) of [[Islamist]] party [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan|Jamaat-e-Islami]], [[Pakistan]].<ref name=Dawn>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1096635/sirajul-haq-elected-as-new-ji-chief|title=Sirajul Haq elected as new (Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan) JI chief|newspaper=Dawn (newspaper)|date=30 March 2014|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and career==\nMunawar Hasan was born in [[Dehli]], [[British India]] on 5 August 1941. At the time of the [[partition of India]], he migrated with his family and settled in [[Karachi]]. He obtained a [[Master's degree]] in sociology in 1963, and in [[Islamic Studies]] in 1966 from the [[University of Karachi]]. Munawar Hasan joined the [[National Students Federation]], a student group, and was elected its president in 1959. The real change appeared in his life when he came closer to the activists of [[Islami Jamiat-e-Talaba]] Pakistan and studied the writings of [[Abul Ala Maududi|Mawlana Syed Abul Ala Maududi]] and Maulana [[Naeem Siddiqui]]. As a result, he joined Islami Jamiat-e-Talaba in 1960 and was elected president of its [[University of Karachi]] unit, Karachi City Unit, and a member of its Central Executive Council. He became its national president in 1964 and served in that capacity for three consecutive terms. During his tenure the Jamiat organised several campaigns mobilising public opinion regarding education issues.<ref name=Dawn3/>\n\nHe joined the Islamic Research Academy and later [[Islamic Jerusalem Studies]], at Karachi as a research assistant in 1963. He became its secretary general in 1969. Under his supervision, the academy published 70 scholarly books. He also served as managing editor of ''The Criterion'' and ''The Universal Message'', [[Karachi]].\n\nMunawar Hasan became a member of [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan|Jama'at-e-Islami Pakistan]] in 1967. He served the Karachi unit as Assistant Secretary, Secretary, Deputy Ameer and Ameer of the city. He was then elected to the Central Shura and the Executive Council of the Jama'at. He represented the group at several platforms, including [[United Democratic Front (Pakistan)|United Democratic Front]] and the [[Pakistan National Alliance]] formed by many Pakistani political parties. He ran for the seat of the [[National Assembly of Pakistan]] in 1977 and secured the highest vote tally in Pakistan. He was Assistant Secretary General of Jama'at-e-Islami Pakistan in 1992\u201393 and became Secretary General in 1993. He was elected [[Emir]] or head of the party in 2009.<ref name=Dawn3/> He was known for his simple living style and was cited as an example, \"For decades he lived in a two-room portion in the house of Jamaat leader Naimatullah Khan in Karachi, content with the stipend from his party.\"<ref name=Dawn3/> Munawar Hasan had always been more of an ideologue rather than a pragmatic leader trying to form political alliances with other parties in Pakistan.<ref name=Dawn1/><ref name=Dawn3>{{cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1080701 |newspaper=Dawn (newspaper)|date=16 January 2014|title=When an ideologue is popular|author=Asha'ar Rehman|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Pakistani general election, 2013==\nAfter the big loss by the Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan (JI) in the [[Pakistani general election, 2013]], Munawar Hasan took full responsibility of it as head of the party and offered to resign from his position, but the Executive Council (Shura Council) of the party refused to accept his resignation.<ref name=Dawn2>{{cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1015415/ji-rejects-munawars-resignation |title=JI (Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan) rejects Munawar's resignation|newspaper=Dawn (newspaper)|date=2 June 2013|author=Khalid Hasnain|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn late March 2014, Munawwar Hasan became the first sitting emir or head in the history of JI to be voted out of office when [[Siraj-ul-Haq Khan]] was elected Ameer by the Jamaat Arakeen (JI members with voting rights). The party chief is elected for a period of five years by the members of the party.<ref name=Dawn/> At least one analyst, Nasir Jamal, attributed the change in leadership to JI Arakeen's desire for a relatively younger and more pragmatic Ameer.<ref name=Dawn1>{{cite news|last1=Jamal|first1=Nasir|title=Analysis: Why Jamaat discarded Munawar Hasan|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1096947|newspaper=Dawn (newspaper)|date=1 April 2014|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=Dawn/><ref name=Dawn2/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Naeem Siddiqui]]\n* Tehreek e Islami\n* [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan]]\n* [[Abdul Ghafoor Ahmed|Prof. Ghafoor Ahmed]]\n* [[Qazi Hussain Ahmad]]\n* [[Liaqat Baloch]]\n* [[Sayyid Abul Ala Maududi]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://jamaat.org/ Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan Official Website]\n\n{{S-start}}\n\n{{s-ppo}}\n\n{{Succession box|title=[[Emir|Ameer]] of [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan|Jamaat-e-Islami]]|\nyears=2009\u20132014|\nbefore=[[Qazi Hussain Ahmad]]|\nafter= [[Siraj ul Haq]]}}\n\n{{end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hasan, Munawwar}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Delhi]]\n[[Category:Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Karachi alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Karachi]]\n[[Category:Pakistani MNAs 1977]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Pakistani English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   =\n|name               = Syed Munawwar Hasan\n|native_name        = \u0633\u06cc\u062f \u0645\u0646\u0648\u0631 \u062d\u0633\u0646\n|native_name_lang   = ur\n|honorific-suffix   = \n|image              =\n|imagesize          = \n|smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n|alt                = \n|caption            = \n|order              = [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan|Emir of Jamaat-e-Islami]]\n|office             = \n|term_start         = 29 March 2009\n|term_end           = 29 March 2014\n|succeeding         = \n|predecessor        = [[Qazi Hussain Ahmad]]\n|successor          = [[Siraj-ul-Haq]]\n|birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1941|08|05}}\n|birth_place        = [[Dehli]], [[British India]]\n|nationality        = [[British Subject]] (1944\u20131947)<br/>{{PAK}} (1947\u2013present)\n|party              = [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan|Jamaat-e-Islami]]\n|occupation         = Religious Leader,<br/>Politician,<br/>Foreign policy commentator\n|alma_mater         = [[University of Peshawar]]<br/>(<small>BSc, MSc</small>)\n|profession         = Professor, religious leader\n}}\n\n'''Syed Munawar Hasan''' ({{lang-ur| \u0633\u06cc\u062f \u0645\u0646\u0648\u0631 \u062d\u0633\u0646}}; (born 5 August 1941) in [[Dehli]]) is a politician and the former [[Emir|Ameer]] (President) of [[Islamist]] party [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan|Jamaat-e-Islami]], [[Pakistan]].<ref name=Dawn>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1096635/sirajul-haq-elected-as-new-ji-chief|title=Sirajul Haq elected as new (Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan) JI chief|newspaper=Dawn (newspaper)|date=30 March 2014|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and career==\nMunawar Hasan was born in [[Dehli]], [[British India]] on 5 August 1941. At the time of the [[partition of India]], he migrated with his family and settled in [[Karachi]]. He obtained a [[Master's degree]] in sociology in 1963, and in [[Islamic Studies]] in 1966 from the [[University of Karachi]]. Munawar Hasan joined the [[National Students Federation]], a student group, and was elected its president in 1959. The real change appeared in his life when he came closer to the activists of [[Islami Jamiat-e-Talaba]] Pakistan and studied the writings of [[Abul Ala Maududi|Mawlana Syed Abul Ala Maududi]] and Maulana [[Naeem Siddiqui]]. As a result, he joined Islami Jamiat-e-Talaba in 1960 and was elected president of its [[University of Karachi]] unit, Karachi City Unit, and a member of its Central Executive Council. He became its national president in 1964 and served in that capacity for three consecutive terms. During his tenure the Jamiat organised several campaigns mobilising public opinion regarding education issues.<ref name=Dawn3/>\n\nHe joined the Islamic Research Academy and later [[Islamic Jerusalem Studies]], at Karachi as a research assistant in 1963. He became its secretary general in 1969. Under his supervision, the academy published 70 scholarly books. He also served as managing editor of ''The Criterion'' and ''The Universal Message'', [[Karachi]].\n\nMunawar Hasan became a member of [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan|Jama'at-e-Islami Pakistan]] in 1967. He served the Karachi unit as Assistant Secretary, Secretary, Deputy Ameer and Ameer of the city. He was then elected to the Central Shura and the Executive Council of the Jama'at. He represented the group at several platforms, including [[United Democratic Front (Pakistan)|United Democratic Front]] and the [[Pakistan National Alliance]] formed by many Pakistani political parties. He ran for the seat of the [[National Assembly of Pakistan]] in 1977 and secured the highest vote tally in Pakistan. He was Assistant Secretary General of Jama'at-e-Islami Pakistan in 1992\u201393 and became Secretary General in 1993. He was elected [[Emir]] or head of the party in 2009.<ref name=Dawn3/> He was known for his simple living style and was cited as an example, \"For decades he lived in a two-room portion in the house of Jamaat leader Naimatullah Khan in Karachi, content with the stipend from from his party.\"<ref name=Dawn3/> Munawar Hasan had always been more of an ideologue rather than a pragmatic leader trying to form political alliances with other parties in Pakistan.<ref name=Dawn1/><ref name=Dawn3>{{cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1080701 |newspaper=Dawn (newspaper)|date=16 January 2014|title=When an ideologue is popular|author=Asha'ar Rehman|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Pakistani general election, 2013==\nAfter the big loss by the Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan (JI) in the [[Pakistani general election, 2013]], Munawar Hasan took full responsibility of it as head of the party and offered to resign from his position, but the Executive Council (Shura Council) of the party refused to accept his resignation.<ref name=Dawn2>{{cite news|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1015415/ji-rejects-munawars-resignation |title=JI (Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan) rejects Munawar's resignation|newspaper=Dawn (newspaper)|date=2 June 2013|author=Khalid Hasnain|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn late March 2014, Munawwar Hasan became the first sitting emir or head in the history of JI to be voted out of office when [[Siraj-ul-Haq Khan]] was elected Ameer by the Jamaat Arakeen (JI members with voting rights). The party chief is elected for a period of five years by the members of the party.<ref name=Dawn/> At least one analyst, Nasir Jamal, attributed the change in leadership to JI Arakeen's desire for a relatively younger and more pragmatic Ameer.<ref name=Dawn1>{{cite news|last1=Jamal|first1=Nasir|title=Analysis: Why Jamaat discarded Munawar Hasan|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1096947|newspaper=Dawn (newspaper)|date=1 April 2014|accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=Dawn/><ref name=Dawn2/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Naeem Siddiqui]]\n* Tehreek e Islami\n* [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan]]\n* [[Abdul Ghafoor Ahmed|Prof. Ghafoor Ahmed]]\n* [[Qazi Hussain Ahmad]]\n* [[Liaqat Baloch]]\n* [[Sayyid Abul Ala Maududi]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://jamaat.org/ Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan Official Website]\n\n{{S-start}}\n\n{{s-ppo}}\n\n{{Succession box|title=[[Emir|Ameer]] of [[Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan|Jamaat-e-Islami]]|\nyears=2009\u20132014|\nbefore=[[Qazi Hussain Ahmad]]|\nafter= [[Siraj ul Haq]]}}\n\n{{end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hasan, Munawwar}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Delhi]]\n[[Category:Jamaat-e-Islami Pakistan politicians]]\n[[Category:University of Karachi alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Karachi]]\n[[Category:Pakistani MNAs 1977]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Munawar_Hasan"}
{"title_page": "16-Methylene-17\u03b1-hydroxyprogesterone acetate", "text_new": "{{Drugbox\n| Verifiedfields = \n| Watchedfields = \n| verifiedrevid = \n| IUPAC_name = [(8''R'',9''S'',10''R'',13''S'',14''S'',17''R'')-17-Acetyl-10,13-dimethyl-16-methylidene-3-oxo-1,2,6,7,8,9,11,12,14,15-decahydrocyclopenta[''a'']phenanthren-17-yl] acetate\n| image = 16-Methylene-17\u03b1-hydroxyprogesterone acetate.svg\n| width = 250px\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename = \n| pregnancy_AU = <!-- A / B1 / B2 / B3 / C / D / X -->\n| pregnancy_US = <!-- A / B / C / D / X -->\n| pregnancy_category = \n| legal_AU = <!-- Unscheduled / S2 / S3 / S4 / S5 / S6 / S7 / S8 / S9 -->\n| legal_CA = \n| legal_UK = \n| legal_US = \n| legal_status = \n| routes_of_administration = \n| class = [[Progestogen]]; [[Progestin]]; [[Progestogen ester]]\n\n<!--Pharmacokinetic data-->\n| bioavailability = \n| protein_bound = \n| metabolism = \n| elimination_half-life = \n| excretion = \n\n<!-- Identifiers -->\n| CAS_number_Ref = \n| CAS_number = 6815-51-6\n| CAS_supplemental = \n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII = XYO20AWR0I\n| ATC_prefix = \n| ATC_suffix = \n| ATC_supplemental = \n| PubChem = 151431\n| IUPHAR_ligand = \n| DrugBank_Ref = \n| DrugBank = \n| ChemSpiderID_Ref = \n| ChemSpiderID = 133463\n| KEGG = \n| ChEBI = \n| ChEMBL = \n| synonyms = 16-Methylene-17\u03b1-acetoxyprogesterone; 16-Methylene-17\u03b1-acetoxypregn-4-en-3,20-dione\n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C=24 | H=32 | O=4\n| molecular_weight = 384.516 g/mol\n| SMILES = CC(=O)[C@]1(C(=C)C[C@@H]2[C@@]1(CC[C@H]3[C@H]2CCC4=CC(=O)CC[C@]34C)C)OC(=O)C\n| StdInChI_Ref = \n| StdInChI = 1S/C24H32O4/c1-14-12-21-19-7-6-17-13-18(27)8-10-22(17,4)20(19)9-11-23(21,5)24(14,15(2)25)28-16(3)26/h13,19-21H,1,6-12H2,2-5H3/t19-,20+,21+,22+,23+,24+/m1/s1\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = \n| StdInChIKey = XSNMCQGNVPSIQM-CKOZHMEPSA-N\n}}\n\n'''16-Methylene-17\u03b1-hydroxyprogesterone acetate''' is a [[progestin]] of the [[17\u03b1-hydroxyprogesterone]] group which was never marketed.<ref name=\"KirkPetrow1960\">{{cite journal|last1=Kirk|first1=D. N.|last2=Petrow|first2=V.|last3=Stansfield|first3=M.|last4=Williamson|first4=D. M.|title=481. Modified steroid hormones. Part XIV. 17\u03b1-Acetoxy-16-methylenepregn-4-ene-3,20-dione|journal=J. Chem. Soc.|volume=0|issue=0|year=1960|pages=2385\u20132388|issn=0368-1769|doi=10.1039/JR9600002385}}</ref><ref name=\"MannhardtWerder1960\">{{cite journal | last1 = Mannhardt | first1 = HJ | last2 = von Werder | first2 = F | last3 = Bork | first3 = KH | last4 = Ketz | first4 = H | last5 = Bruckner | first5 = K | title = Preparation of 16-methylene steroids of the corticoid and progesterone series | journal = Tetrahedron Letters | issue = 16 | pages = 21-32 | year = 1960 | issn = 0040-4039}}</ref><ref name=\"Syhora1961\">{{cite journal | last1 = Syhora | first1 = K | title = Steroid derivatives. IX. Partial synthesis of 17\u03b1-acetoxy-16-methyleneprogesterone | journal = Collection of Czechoslovak Chemical Communications | volume = 26 | pages = 1034\u20138 | year = 1961 | issn = 0010-0765 | doi=10.1135/cccc19611034}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid14056440\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Shapiro E, Legatt T, Weber L, Steinberg M, Watnick A, Eisler M, Hennessey MG, Coniglio CT, Charney W, Oliveto EP | title = 16-Alkylated Progesterones | journal = J Med Pharm Chem | volume = 91 | issue = | pages = 975\u201388 | date = September 1962 | pmid = 14056440 | doi = 10.1021/jm01240a010 | url = }}</ref><ref name=\"\u010cekan\u0160eda1964\">{{cite journal|last1=\u010cekan|first1=Z.|last2=\u0160eda|first2=M.|last3=Mikul\u00e1\u0161kov\u00e1|first3=J.|last4=Syhora|first4=K.|title=Steroid derivatives XXXIV. On the progestational activity of 6-dehydro-16-methylene-17\u03b1-acetoxyprogesterone|journal=Steroids|volume=4|issue=3|year=1964|pages=415\u2013421|issn=0039128X|doi=10.1016/0039-128X(64)90154-0}}</ref> Given [[oral administration|orally]], it shows about 2.5-fold the [[progestogen]]ic activity of [[parenteral]] [[progesterone (medication)|progesterone]] in animal [[bioassay]]s.<ref name=\"\u010cekan\u0160eda1964\" /> It is a [[parent compound]] of the following clinically used progestins:<ref name=\"Milne2017\">{{cite book|author=G.W.A Milne|title=Ashgate Handbook of Endocrine Agents and Steroids|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GFM8DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT158|date=1 November 2017|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-351-74347-1|pages=158\u2013162}}</ref><ref name=\"DenkewalterTishler2013\">{{cite book|author1=R. G. Denkewalter|author2=M. Tishler|author3=G. Ehrhart|author4=J. H. Biel|author5=B. K. B. Lum|author6=J. B\u00fcchi|author7=C. A. Winter|author8=K. M\u00fcnzel|author9=W. Kunz|author10=E. J. Ari\u00ebns|author11=F. Labhardt|title=Fortschritte der Arzneimittelforschung / Progress in Drug Research / Progr\u00e8s des recherches pharmaceutiques|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZSH3BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA407|date=8 March 2013|publisher=Birkh\u00e4user|isbn=978-3-0348-7059-7|pages=407\u2013}}</ref>\n\n* [[Chlormethenmadinone acetate]] (6-chloro-16-methylene-17\u03b1-hydroxy-\u0394<sup>6</sup>-progesterone acetate)\n* [[Melengestrol acetate]] (6-methyl-16-methylene-17\u03b1-hydroxy-\u0394<sup>6</sup>-progesterone acetate)\n* [[Methenmadinone acetate]] (16-methylene-17\u03b1-hydroxy-\u0394<sup>6</sup>-progesterone acetate)\n* [[Segesterone acetate]] (16-methylene-17\u03b1-hydroxy-19-norprogesterone acetate)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{Progesterone receptor modulators}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Methylene-17\u03b1-hydroxyprogesterone acetate, 16-}}\n[[Category:Abandoned drugs]]\n[[Category:Acetate esters]]\n[[Category:Diketones]]\n[[Category:Pregnanes]]\n[[Category:Progestogens]]\n\n\n{{Steroid-stub}}\n{{Genito-urinary-drug-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Drugbox\n| Verifiedfields = \n| Watchedfields = \n| verifiedrevid = \n| IUPAC_name = [(8''R'',9''S'',10''R'',13''S'',14''S'',17''R'')-17-Acetyl-10,13-dimethyl-16-methylidene-3-oxo-1,2,6,7,8,9,11,12,14,15-decahydrocyclopenta[''a'']phenanthren-